    {
      "number": 6,
      "id": "I_kwDOJQZP185ixRGh",
      "title": "Compute and round trip tradeoffs",
      "url": "https://github.com/chris-wood/draft-crypto-deployment-considerations/issues/6",
      "state": "OPEN",
      "author": "chris-wood",
      "authorAssociation": "OWNER",
      "assignees": [],
      "labels": [],
      "body": "From @bwesterb:\r\n\r\n> \"However, minimizing the cost of this step is only useful up to the point where the cost of network round trips exceeds that of the key exchange computation.\"\r\n> \r\n> Nit picking: this suggests that if key exchange is faster than the RTT (or something like that), that it's then fast enough. Don't think that is: we'd need to buy a lot of extra servers and it'd be a big drain on battery if a single kex takes 50ms. Also except for keygen, key exchange can't be done in parallel, so it's always a bottleneck so to say.\r\n\r\nThis is a fair point and something worth clarifying further.",
      "createdAt": "2023-04-06T09:57:20Z",
      "updatedAt": "2023-04-06T09:57:20Z",
      "closedAt": null,
      "comments": []
    },
    {
      "number": 7,
      "id": "I_kwDOJQZP185ixRyI",
      "title": "Round trips and bandwidth",
      "url": "https://github.com/chris-wood/draft-crypto-deployment-considerations/issues/7",
      "state": "OPEN",
      "author": "chris-wood",
      "authorAssociation": "OWNER",
      "assignees": [],
      "labels": [],
      "body": "High bandwidth costs may increase round trips at the transport layer, e.g., if congestion windows fill up and can only be cleared via explicit acknowledgements. ",
